'''''Gangbusters''''' is a 1982 strategy video game about the [[American Mafia]] for the [[Commodore 64]]. The game is set during [[Prohibition in the United States|Prohibition]] in the early 1920s. The game appeared in the December 1982 issue of ''[[The Rainbow (magazine)|The Rainbow]]''. Due to various glitches, the game failed to work on 16K machines but worked reliably on most 32K machines.<ref name="dydns"/> A complete set of documents were included with the game that taught the players the complete [[glossary]] of the Mafia "language.<ref name="dydns">{{cite web| url = http://cocomag.dyndns.org/cgi-bin/show_magazine.pl?magazine=TheRainbow&issue=820206&article=820206-005-toc-39.cktct| title = Gangbusters, The Rainbow, Volume 2, Number 6, December 1982| publisher = Dydns.org| date = | accessdate = 2011-09-14}}{{Dead link|date=March 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>"

==Summary==
[[File:Gangbusters title.png|thumb|left|Title screen]]
[[File:GangbustersScreenshotC64.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|Gangbusters]]
Each player tries to get promoted from [[criminal|punk]] to [[capo di tutti capi|Godfather]] by purchasing a [[gun]] and attempting to [[murder]] someone.<ref name="mobygames">{{cite web | url = http://www.mobygames.com/game/gangbusters| title = Basic game overview | publisher = [[MobyGames]]| date = | accessdate = 2011-03-19}}</ref> If convicted, the "[[district attorney|state mouthpiece]]" will sentence the player to four years in [[prison]]. For each subsequent sentence, the sentence is doubled unless a [[pardon]] can be purchased from the "state mouthpiece". Players can purchase [[truck]]ing [[trade union|union]]s, [[Prostitution|prostitute]]s that are all assigned with the code name ''Betsy'', and [[moonshine]] operations.<ref name="mobygames"/> [[Limousine]]s can be stolen from other players who already have them, with a certain degree of risk.<ref name="mobygames"/> Betting on [[horse racing]] events can play a role in adding valuable dollars to the player's bank account.<ref name="dydns"/>

All games end either when the last remaining player has become the Godfather or the [[Federal government of the United States|United States government]] becomes wise and defeats all the players.<ref name="mobygames"/> The game assigns each player a different [[United States|American]] city like [[Brooklyn]] or [[Philadelphia]] from which to run his domain.

==Reception==
Andy Peters for ''[[The Rainbow (magazine)|The Rainbow]]'' said "If you've ever dreamed of living a life of crime, ''Gangbusters'' is an excellent way to get started, keeping you both safe and innocent!"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.org/details/198212Rainbow/page/n159/mode/2up|title=198212 Rainbow|date=December 15, 1982|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

Roy Wagner for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' said "The program offers colorful book-keeping and flawless tabulation. It has very limited graphics, but is an intriguing game with more than one strategy which can win."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.org/details/Computer_Gaming_World_Issue_3.6/page/n37/mode/2up|title=Computer Gaming World Issue 3.6|date=December 15, 1983|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

